{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616143"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16386"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16386"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.11,0.64,0,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74644"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9077"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7114"},{"type":"tags","id":"7116"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21577"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74644"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary somatosensory cortex is a region of the brain that receives and processes sensory information from the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location of the primary somatosensory cortex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Postcentral gyrus in frontal lobe","Precentral gyrus in frontal lobe","Postcentral gyrus in parietal lobe","Striate cortex in temporal lobe","Precentral gyrus in parietal lobe"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epostcentral gyrus in the parietal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E is the location of the primary somatosensory cortex (S1). This area processes sensory information from the body in a topographically organised manner known as the sensory homunculus. The postcentral gyrus is located immediately posterior to the central sulcus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epostcentral gyrus in the frontal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E is anatomically incorrect as the postcentral gyrus is, by definition, in the parietal lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprecentral gyrus in the frontal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E is the location of the primary motor cortex (M1), which controls voluntary movement. It is located immediately anterior to the central sulcus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Estriate cortex in the temporal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect anatomically. The striate cortex (V1) is the primary visual cortex located in the occipital lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprecentral gyrus in the parietal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E is anatomically incorrect as the precentral gyrus is, by definition, in the frontal lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the location of the primary somatosensory cortex is crucial for interpreting neurological symptoms and signs. Lesions affecting this area typically result in contralateral sensory deficits, while those affecting the primary motor cortex in the precentral gyrus cause contralateral motor deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The primary somatosensory cortex is located in the postcentral gyrus of the parietal lobe.","The primary somatosensory cortex receives and processes sensory information from the body in a topographically organised manner (homunculus).","The postcentral gyrus lies immediately posterior to the central sulcus, while the precentral gyrus (motor cortex) lies anterior to it."],"references":["Raju H, Tadi P. Neuroanatomy, Somatosensory Cortex. [Updated 2022 Nov 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555915/","Souza-Couto D, Bretas R, Aversi-Ferreira TA. Neuropsychology of the parietal lobe: Luria\u0027s and contemporary conceptions. Front Neurosci. 2023 Oct 20;17:1226226. doi: 10.3389/fnins.2023.1226226. PMID: 37928730; PMCID: PMC10623013","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16386"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T10:33:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T10:34:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9077"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74644"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data"